      • getImpliedPriceDecimalPlaces

        public int getImpliedPriceDecimalPlaces()
        Description copied from interface: IInstrument
        Returns the number of implied decimal places in a price for this instrument.

        For example, if prices for this instrument are quoted in dollars and cents, this method may return the value 2. This indicates that the int values returned by methods in this interface for prices have two implied decimal places. For example, a returned price of 125 indicates a price of 1.25.

        Specified by:
        getImpliedPriceDecimalPlaces in interface IInstrument
        Returns:
        int The number of implied decimal places in returned prices for this instrument.

      • getInternalID

        public int getInternalID()
        Description copied from interface: IInstrument
        Returns unique int ID assigned to this instrument for the duration of this application (ie the life of the JVM).

        This ID is unique for every instrument object in this application. It is assigned automatically when the instrument is created. Note, however, that each time an application is launched, an instrument may be assigned a different ID.

        ID's start at 1 and increase incrementally - so it is practical to use this ID as an array index.

        It is useful within an application for quickly looking up instruments. It can be used as the basis of the standard equals and hashCode methods.

        Specified by:
        getInternalID in interface IInstrument
        Returns:
        Unique ID for this instrument. Always non zero positive.

      • setMarketDataService

        public void setMarketDataService(IMarketDataService marketDataService)
        Normally for internal use only.

        This is called automatically when an instrument is created in MarketDataServiceBase.createInstrument.

        The only time you might need to call it is if you write a market data service that does not subclass MarketDataServiceBase or which overrides the createInstrument method and does not call the base method implementation (eg super.createInstrument(...))

        Parameters:
        marketDataService - Market data service to which this instrument belongs.

      • setTopOfBook

        public void setTopOfBook(StandardUpdateEntry[] changes)
        Processing of the changes array terminates once an entry with a 0 fieldID is encountered. This allows an array to be reused for passing in events. For example, a market data service could allocate a large array of StandardUpdateEntry objects, and just use the entries required on each update, delimited by an empty entry (fieldID <= 0).
        Specified by:
        setTopOfBook in interface ITopOfBookUpdate
        Parameters:
        changes - Array of StandardUpdateEntry

      • setSecurityDefinition

        public void setSecurityDefinition(StandardUpdateEntry[] changes)
        Description copied from interface: ISecurityDefinitionUpdate
        Update the security definition data contained in the passed array of changes.

        In a FIX environment, it is important that all changes relating to a given FIX security definition should appear together in the changes array.

        Processing of the changes array terminates once an entry with a 0 fieldID is encountered. This allows an array to be reused for passing in events. For example, a market data service could allocate a large array of StandardUpdateEntry objects, and just use the entries required on each update, delimited by an empty entry (fieldID <= 0).

        Specified by:
        setSecurityDefinition in interface ISecurityDefinitionUpdate
        Parameters:
        changes - Array of StandardUpdateEntry containing field ID's and their updated values.

        Sets top of book data - ie best bid, ask and last trade information.

        Special values:

        • IInstrument.VALUE_NONE Not present - eg no bids, asks or never traded.
        • IInstrument.VALUE_UNKNOWN: Unknown
        • IInstrument.VALUE_UNCHANGED: Unchanged. Stored value is not updated.
        • IInstrument.VALUE_UNSUPPORTED: For example, if a market data source did not support quantities for top of book data, then all quantities would always be passed in with this value.
        Parameters:
        bidQty - New best bid (buy) quantity.
        bid - New best bid (buy) price.
        askQty - New best ask (sell) quantity.
        ask - New best ask (sell) price.
        lastQty - New last trade quantity.
        last - New last traded price.

      • addDepthEntry

        public IDepthEntry addDepthEntry(boolean buy,
                                 int price,
                                 int qty,
                                 IMarketDataItem[] values)
        Description copied from interface: IDepthUpdate
        Adds a new depth entry.

        If an entry at this price level already exists, the quantity specified is added to the quantity in the existing entry.

        Processing of the values array terminates once an entry with a 0 fieldID is encountered. This allows an array to be reused for passing in events.

        If one of the explicit fields, (ie buy, price or qty), also is specified in the values array, the values array entry is ignored - in other words the explicit field value takes precedence.

        Note that StandardUpdateEntry is an IMarketData, so that an array of StandardUpdateEntry's can be passed in as the values if you wish.

        Specified by:
        addDepthEntry in interface IDepthUpdate
        Parameters:
        buy - True if this is a buy side entry.
        price - Price level of this entry.
        qty - Quantity of entry.
        values - Any additional information associated with this entry. May be null.
        Returns:
        The object used to store details on this depth entry.

      • changeDepth

        public void changeDepth(IDetailEntry[] buyDepth,
                        IDetailEntry[] sellDepth)

      • changeDepth

        public void changeDepth(IDetailEntry[] buyDepth,
                        IDetailEntry[] sellDepth,
                        gnu.trove.map.hash.TLongObjectHashMap<IDepthEntry> idMap)
        Description copied from interface: IDepthUpdate
        Replaces whole depth in a single call.

        Any previous depth information is discarded.

        The most competitive entry should be at index 0 in the array.

        Note that the data passed in is in the form of IDetailEntry's rather that IDepthEntry's. Note that IDepthEntry extends IDetailEntry and the extra information required by IDepthEntry is not required.

        Processing of the array will stop at the first entry with qty == 0. This means that the same fixed size array object can be reused for passing in data in successive calls, since only non empty entries in the array will be processed - extra entries will be ignored.

        Specified by:
        changeDepth in interface IDepthUpdate
        Parameters:
        buyDepth - Buy side depth entries
        sellDepth - Sell side depth entries
        idMap - Used for mapping external ID's on the detail entries to the ID's used to reference the detail entries internally. May be null, in which case any ID's on the detail entries are ignored completely.

        Adds a new detail entry with the given characteristics to the list of existing detail entries at the specified price level.

        Processing of the values array terminates once an entry with a 0 fieldID is encountered. This allows an array to be reused for passing in events.

        If one of the explicit fields, (ie buy, position, price or qty), also is specified in the values array, the values array entry is ignored - in other words the explicit field value takes precedence.

        addDetailEntry in interface IDetailUpdate
        Parameters:
        buy - True if this is a buy side entry.

        qty - Quantity of entry.
        values - Any additional information associated with this entry - for example the broker associated with the entry. May be null.
